    <comment_count>6</comment_count>
    <who name="Jaak Ristioja">jaak</who>
    <bug_when>2011-11-25 19:42:23 +0200</bug_when>
    <thetext>(In reply to comment #5)
&gt; (In reply to comment #3)
&gt; &gt; I&apos;m Portuguese and i&apos;ve even started the translation of BibleTime into Pt-Pt...
&gt; &gt; however, since i didn&apos;t saw any way to change the language, i stopped. I
&gt; &gt; thought that in the absense of the pt-pt language file, it would fall into
&gt; &gt; pt-br or allow a user to select the prefered language!
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; But now, from what you&apos;re saying, i&apos;m starting to think that BibleTime works
&gt; &gt; fine and, because it does not have a pt-pt, it does fall into english
&gt; &gt; language... is that it?
&gt; 
&gt; Something like that, yes. I could try to make the fallback algorithm a bit more
&gt; intelligent. I might even manage to get it into 2.9.0.

By the looks of it, there fallback algorithm provided by Qt appears to be rather good. The problem at hand is caused by the way we have named the translation files.

If QLocale::system().name() returns &quot;pt_PT&quot; for your system, then BibleTime will search (in order) for the following files in the translations directory:

  bibletime_ui_pt_PT.qm
  bibletime_ui_pt_PT
  bibletime_ui_pt.qm
  bibletime_ui_pt
  bibletime_ui.qm
  bibletime_ui
  bibletime.qm
  bibletime

The bibletime_ui_pt_BR.qm file just doesn&apos;t happen to be on that list. But the file can easily and should probably be renamed. I guess we have similar problems with other translations.</thetext>
